<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>

<worksheet>
  <title>EL-1 Exponential and Logarithmic Functions</title>
  <introduction>
    <p>
      This outcome covers exponential and logarithmic functions and models. You should be able to rewrite exponential functions
      in various forms. Be able to find the domain, range, and intercepts of the function.  You should also be 
      able to graph exponential and logarithmic functions. Here you will also be asked to setup and solve real-world problems 
      using exponential and logarithmic models. You should be able to write out complete steps to solve these 
      types of problems by hand, without the use of a calculator.
    </p>
    <p>For the quiz on this outcome you would be given 30 minutes to complete 3 problems. Here are samples 
      of the types of problems you will encounter:</p>
  </introduction>
  <objectives>
    <ul>
      <li><p>Simplifying Expressions: Simplify algebraic expressions by combining like terms and applying the 
        distributive property. Answers should be completely simplified.</p></li>
        <li><p>Basics of Graphing: Give a graph with appropriate scales and labels. The line should have the 
          correct intercepts and general behavior.</p></li>
      <li><p>Problem structure: Solution should be organized and easy to follow, with clear, complete steps 
        that follow progressively from one to the next.</p></li>
      <li><p>Mathematical Communication: Solutions should be presented in a clear and logical manner, with 
        appropriate use of mathematical notation and terminology. Equations should have at most one equal 
        sign and expressions on both sides.</p></li>
      <li><p>Find attributes: Identify and state the domain, range, intercepts, and asymptotes of exponential 
        and logarithmic functions. Note: Domains and ranges should be expressed in interval notation. All values 
      should be simplified and expressed in terms of natural logarithms where applicable.</p></li>
      <li><p>Graph exponential and logarithmic functions.</p></li>
      <li><p>Given an exponential or logarithmic graph, write an equation for the function.</p></li>
    </ul>
    </objectives>

  
  <page>
    <exercise workspace="3cm">
      <introduction><p>
           Given <m>f(x)=\left(\frac{3}{4}\right)^{x+2}-3</m>.
        </p></introduction>
        <task>
            <statement><p>State the domain and range.</p></statement>
            <hint><p>Recall that the domain of an exponential function is all real numbers, and the range 
              depends on the vertical shift.</p></hint>
            <answer><p>Domain: <m>(-\infty, \infty)</m>; Range: <m>(-3, \infty)</m></p></answer>
            <solution><p>The domain of an exponential function is always all real numbers. The range 
              depends on the vertical shift. Since the function is shifted down by 3 units, the range 
              is <m>(-3, \infty)</m>.</p></solution>
        </task>
        <task>
            <statement><p>State the intercepts.</p></statement>
            <hint><p>To find the y-intercept, set <m>x=0</m>. To find the x-intercept, set <m>y=0</m>.</p></hint>
            <answer><p>y-intercept: <m>(0, -\frac{39}{16})</m>; x-intercept: <m>(\frac{\ln3}{\ln\frac{3}{4}}+2,0)</m>
            </p></answer>
            <solution><p>To find the y-intercept, set <m>x=0</m>: <m>f(0)=\left(\frac{3}{4}\right)^{0+2}-3
              =\left(\frac{3}{4}\right)^{2}-3=\frac{9}{16}-3=-\frac{39}{16}</m>. So the y-intercept is 
              <m>(0, -\frac{39}{16})</m>. To find the x-intercept, set <m>y=0</m>: <m>0=\left(\frac{3}{4}\right)^{x+2}-3</m>. 
              <m>\left(\frac{3}{4}\right)^{x+2}=3</m>. Taking the natural logarithm of both sides and dividing gives 
              <m>x+2=\frac{\ln3}{\ln\frac{3}{4}}</m>. Therefore, the x-intercept is 
              <m>\left(\frac{\ln3}{\ln\frac{3}{4}}+2,0\right)</m>.</p></solution>
        </task>
        <task>
            <statement><p>State the asymptote(s).</p></statement>
            <hint><p>Exponential functions have horizontal asymptotes, while logarithmic functions 
              have vertical asymptotes.</p></hint>
            <answer><p>Horizontal asymptote: <m>y=-3</m></p></answer>
            <solution><p>Exponential functions have horizontal asymptotes determined by the vertical shift. 
              Since the function is shifted down by 3 units, the horizontal asymptote is <m>y=-3</m>.</p></solution>
        </task>
        <task>
          <statement><p>Graph the function.</p></statement>
          <hint><p>Plot the intercepts and use the asymptote to guide the shape of the graph.</p></hint>
          <answer><p><image width="60%">
              <prefigure xmlns="https://prefigure.org"
                          label="prefigure-el1a-sample">
                <diagram dimensions="(300,300)" margins="5">
                  <definition>f(x)=(3/4)^(x-2)-3</definition>
                  <coordinates bbox="(-10,-10,10,10)">
                    <grid spacings="((-10,2,10),(-10,2,10))"/>
                    <grid-axes xlabel="x" ylabel="y"/>
                    <graph function="f"/>
                    <line endpoints="((-10,-3),(10,-3))" stroke="blue" dash="4 4" label-location="0.1"><m>y=-3</m></line>
                  </coordinates>
              <annotations>
                <annotation ref="figure"
                  text="The graph of the function shows the y-intercept at (0, -\frac{39}{16})
                  and the x-intercept at (\frac{\ln3}{\ln\frac{3}{4}}+2,0). The 
                  horizontal asymptote is shown as a dashed blue line at y=-3. The exponential 
                  curve approaches the asymptote from above as x goes to infinity. The exponential curve
                  approaches infinity as x approaches negative infinity.">
                  </annotation>
              </annotations>
            </diagram>
          </prefigure>
        </image>
      </p></answer>
    </task>
    </exercise>
    <exercise workspace="3cm">
      <introduction><p>
           Given <m>y=4-\log_2(x+3)</m>.
        </p></introduction>
        <task>
            <statement><p>Rewrite the function in exponential form.</p></statement>
            <hint><p>Use the exponential-logarithmic equivalence to rewrite the function.</p></hint>
            <answer><p><m>x=2^{4-y}-3</m></p></answer>
            <solution><p>To rewrite the function in exponential form, we start with the given logarithmic 
              function and begin by isolating the logarithmic term <m>4-y=\log_2(x+3)</m>. Then, we apply 
              the exponential-logarithmic equivalence and solve for <m>x</m>:</p><p><m>x+3=2^{4-y}</m></p>
              <p><m>x=2^{4-y}-3</m></p></solution>
        </task>
        <task>
            <statement><p>State the domain and range.</p></statement>
            <hint><p>Consider the restrictions on the input and output values.</p></hint>
            <answer><p>Domain: <m>(-3, \infty)</m>; Range: <m>(-\infty, \infty)</m></p></answer>
            <solution><p>The domain of the logarithmic function is determined by the requirement 
              that the argument of the logarithm be positive. Thus, <m>x+3>0</m>, which implies <m>x>-3</m>. 
              The range of the logarithmic function is all real numbers, so <m>(-\infty, \infty)</m>.</p></solution>
        </task>
        <task>
            <statement><p>State the intercepts.</p></statement>
            <hint><p>To find the y-intercept, set <m>x=0</m> and solve for <m>y</m>. 
              To find the x-intercept, set <m>y=0</m> and solve for <m>x</m>.</p></hint>
            <answer><p>y-intercept: <m>(0, 4-\frac{\ln 3}{\ln 2})</m>; x-intercept: <m>(13, 0)</m></p></answer>
            <solution><p>To find the y-intercept, set <m>x=0</m> and solve for <m>y</m> and give answer in terms 
              of natural logarithms:</p><p><m>y=4-\frac{\ln 3}{\ln 2}</m></p><p>To find the x-intercept, set 
                <m>y=0</m> and solve for <m>x</m>:</p><p><m>0=4-\log_2(x+3)</m></p><p><m>\log_2(x+3)=4</m></p>
                <p><m>x+3=2^4</m></p><p><m>x=2^4-3</m></p><p><m>x=13</m></p></solution>
        </task>
        <task>
            <statement><p>State the asymptote(s).</p></statement>
            <hint><p>To find the vertical asymptote of the logarithmic function, consider the values of 
              <m>x</m> for which the argument of the logarithm is zero.</p></hint>
            <answer><p>Vertical asymptote: <m>x=-3</m></p></answer>
            <solution><p>The vertical asymptote occurs where the argument of the logarithm is zero. 
              Thus, <m>x+3=0</m>, which implies <m>x=-3</m>.</p></solution>
        </task>
          <task>
            <statement><p>Graph the function.</p></statement>
            <hint><p>Plot the intercepts and use the asymptote to guide the shape of the graph.</p></hint>
            <answer><p><image width="60%">
                <prefigure xmlns="https://prefigure.org"
                            label="prefigure-el1b-sample">
                  <diagram dimensions="(300,300)" margins="5">
                    <definition>y=4-log_2(x+3)</definition>
                    <coordinates bbox="(-10,-10,10,10)">
                      <grid spacings="((-10,2,10),(-10,2,10))"/>
                      <grid-axes xlabel="x" ylabel="y"/>
                      <graph function="y=4-log_2(x+3)"/>
                      <line endpoints="((-3,-10),(-3,10))" stroke="blue" dash="4 4" label-location="0.1"><m>x=-3</m></line>
                    </coordinates>
                <annotations>
                  <annotation ref="figure"
                    text="The graph of the function shows the y-intercept at (0, 4-\frac{\ln 3}{\ln 2})
                    and the x-intercept at (13, 0). The vertical asymptote is shown as a dashed blue line at x=-3. The logarithmic 
                    curve approaches the asymptote from the right as x approaches -3. The logarithmic curve
                    approaches negative infinity as x approaches -3 from the right and approaches infinity as x goes to infinity.">
                        </annotation>
                </annotations>
              </diagram>
            </prefigure></image></p></answer>
          </task>
    </exercise>
    <exercise workspace="3cm">
      <task>
        <statement><p>
           An exponential function has a horizontal asymptote at <m>y=-3</m>. 
           The graph of the function passes through the points <m>(1,1)</m> 
           and <m>(2,5)</m>.  If the function has the form <m>g(x)=a^{x+b}+ c</m> 
           for real numbers <m>a, b</m>, and <m>c</m>, find <m>g(x)</m>.
        </p></statement>
        <hint><p>Use the horizontal asymptote to find <m>c</m>, then use the two given 
          points to find <m>a</m> and <m>b</m>.</p></hint>
        <answer><p>g(x)=2^{x+1}-3</p></answer>
        <solution><p>The horizontal asymptote at <m>y=-3</m> indicates that <m>c=-3</m>. 
          Using the points <m>(1,1)</m> and <m>(2,5)</m>, we can solve for <m>a</m> and <m>b</m>.</p>
        <p><m>1=a^{1+b}-3</m> and <m>5=a^{2+b}-3</m></p><p>Adding 3 to both sides of each equation gives:
          <m>4=a^{1+b}</m> and <m>8=a^{2+b}</m></p><p>Dividing the second equation by the first gives:</p>
          <p><m>\frac{8}{4}=a^{(2+b)-(1+b)}=a</m></p><p><m>a=2</m></p><p>Substituting back into the first equation gives:</p>
          <p><m>4=2^{1+b}</m></p><p><m>2^2=2^{1+b}</m></p><p><m>2=1+b</m></p><p><m>b=1</m></p>
          <p>Thus, the function is <m>g(x)=2^{x+1}-3</m>.</p></solution>
      </task>
    </exercise>
  </page>
</worksheet>